The paper proposes a framework based on convolutional neural networks (CNNs) for automatic sleep staging, which involves both classification and prediction tasks. Therefore, it is likely to belong to the sub-category of Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV). The paper also discusses the advantages of the proposed framework over existing approaches, which suggests that it may belong to the sub-categories of Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE). Additionally, the paper emphasizes the importance of correctly identifying sleep stages for diagnosing and treating sleep disorders, which indicates that it may also belong to the sub-category of Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC).
